\newlabel{tutorial:id13}{{2.1.4}{28}{From the theory (see \phantomsection {\hyperref [\detokenize {tutorial:bis-2013}]{\sphinxcrossref {{[}BIS-2013{]}}}}, \phantomsection {\hyperref [\detokenize {tutorial:adt-l7}]{\sphinxcrossref {{[}ADT-L7{]}}}} ) we know that the bipolarly outranking relation is \sphinxstylestrong {weakly complete}, i.e. if \(r(x\,S\,y) < 0.0\) then \(r(y\,S\,x) >= 0.0\) . From this property follows that the bipolarly valued outranking relation verifies the coduality principle: the dual (-) of the converse (\textasciitilde {}) of the outranking relation corresponds to its strict outranking part. We may visualize the codual (strict) outranking digraph with a graphviz drawing \sphinxfootnotemark [1]:}{section*.73}{}}
\newlabel{tutorial:id14}{{2.1.4}{28}{From the theory (see \phantomsection {\hyperref [\detokenize {tutorial:bis-2013}]{\sphinxcrossref {{[}BIS-2013{]}}}}, \phantomsection {\hyperref [\detokenize {tutorial:adt-l7}]{\sphinxcrossref {{[}ADT-L7{]}}}} ) we know that the bipolarly outranking relation is \sphinxstylestrong {weakly complete}, i.e. if \(r(x\,S\,y) < 0.0\) then \(r(y\,S\,x) >= 0.0\) . From this property follows that the bipolarly valued outranking relation verifies the coduality principle: the dual (-) of the converse (\textasciitilde {}) of the outranking relation corresponds to its strict outranking part. We may visualize the codual (strict) outranking digraph with a graphviz drawing \sphinxfootnotemark [1]:}{section*.74}{}}
